  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is a **Gregorian reflecting telescope** made by the Van der Bildt workshop in Franeker, Friesland — one of the most prolific telescope-making dynasties in 18th-century Europe. The patriarch **Jan Pieters van der Bildt** (1709–1791) manufactured over **550 reflecting telescopes** during his career, rivaling the output of James Short of London. According to a Teylers Museum article, this instrument is a remarkable **dual-system telescope** that can function in both Gregorian mode (concave secondary) and Cassegrain mode (convex secondary), with a brass tube of 630 mm (780 mm with extension), a primary mirror of 108 mm diameter in speculum metal, and Huygens eyepieces including a micrometer eyepiece. It is displayed in vitrine VIII of the Oval Room.",
